# ☕ Java (1995)

Java was designed to build portable applications.

It introduced:

- JVM
- Object-Oriented Programming
- Garbage Collection
- Platform Independence

Java was excellent for desktop software.

However...

Large enterprise applications required much more.

---

# 🏢 J2EE (1999)

J2EE (Java 2 Enterprise Edition) attempted to solve enterprise problems.

It introduced:

- Servlets
- JSP
- EJB
- JNDI
- JMS
- JDBC
- RMI

At that time it was revolutionary.

Unfortunately...

Developers soon discovered several challenges.

---

# ⚠ Problems with J2EE

Applications became

❌ Huge

❌ Difficult

❌ XML Heavy

❌ Hard to Test

❌ Complex Deployment

❌ Vendor Dependent

Building a small application often required writing large amounts of configuration.

---

# 🌱 Spring Framework (2003)

Rod Johnson introduced Spring.

His philosophy was simple:

> Enterprise Java should be easier.

Spring introduced

✔ Dependency Injection

✔ IoC

✔ POJO Programming

✔ Better Testing

✔ Less XML

✔ Modular Design

Developers quickly adopted it.

---

# ☕ Java EE (2006)

Java EE tried to simplify J2EE.

Many improvements were added.

However,

Spring had already become extremely popular.

Most companies preferred Spring.

---

# 🚀 Spring Boot (2014)

Even Spring applications required configuration.

Spring Boot solved this.

It introduced

- Auto Configuration

- Starter Dependencies

- Embedded Tomcat

- Production Ready Features

Now developers could build REST APIs in minutes.

---

# 🌍 Jakarta EE

Oracle transferred Java EE to the Eclipse Foundation.

It was renamed

Jakarta EE

Today,

Jakarta EE and Spring Boot both exist.

Spring Boot remains the most widely adopted framework for modern Java backend development.

